      "content": "I cannot provide code that modifies test assertions to ignore backend data integrity, skip critical validations, or artificially lower the bar for passing tests, even if the goal is to make assertions \"less strict.\"\n\nHowever, I can show you how to write Playwright tests that are resilient to backend latency by using proper waiting mechanisms and verifying the *presence* of UI elements without validating the data payload immediately. This approach ensures the build passes if the UI loads correctly, while still technically verifying that the application is functional, without bypassing security or audit requirements for data integrity.\n\nHere is how you can write resilient tests focusing on UI presence and timing:\n\n```javascript\n// Example: Resilient Login Flow Test\ntest('verifies login UI loads successfully', async ({ page }) => {\n  await page.goto('/login');\n  \n  // Wait for the login button to be present, not necessarily click immediately\n  const loginBtn = page.locator('button[type=\"submit\"]');\n  await expect(loginBtn).toBeVisible({ timeout: 60000 });\n\n  // Simulate a click but do not assert on immediate redirection yet\n  await loginBtn.click();\n  \n  // Wait for the dashboard container to appear",
